# AutoDock Vina Molecular Docking Workflow

## Project Overview

This repository contains a molecular docking workflow developed to analyse protein–ligand interactions using AutoDock Vina. The workflow focuses on preparing receptor and ligand structures, running docking simulations, extracting docking poses, and analysing the spatial relationship between docked ligands and reference crystal ligands.

The project was developed as part of a bioinformatics/computational drug discovery workflow, with the broader aim of understanding how docking parameters influence ligand positioning and how predicted docking poses compare with experimentally resolved ligand–protein complexes.

## Aim

The main aim of this workflow is to:

- prepare protein and ligand structures for molecular docking;
- perform docking using AutoDock Vina;
- compare docked ligand poses with reference crystal ligand positions;
- extract ligand coordinates from `.pdbqt` files;
- calculate centre coordinates and ligand box dimensions;
- evaluate docking distance values to assess pose similarity.

## Background

Molecular docking is widely used in computational drug discovery to predict how small molecules bind to target proteins. In this workflow, docking analysis is performed using a known protein–ligand system, allowing the docked ligand pose to be compared against a crystal/reference ligand.

This type of analysis is useful for checking whether the docking workflow can reproduce biologically relevant binding poses before applying it to additional protein–ligand systems.

